# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: slowly-changing-dimension
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A **dimension** is a structure that categorizes facts and measures in order to enable users to answer business questions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Commonly used dimensions are people, products, place and time.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] In a data warehouse, dimensions provide structured labeling information to otherwise unordered numeric measures.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The dimension is a data set composed of individual, non-overlapping data elements.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The primary functions of dimensions are threefold: to provide filtering, grouping and labelling.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] These functions are often described as "slice and dice".
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A common data warehouse example involves sales as the measure, with customer and product as dimensions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The data can be sliced by removing all customers except for a group under study, and then diced by grouping by product.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A dimensional data element is similar to a categorical variable in statistics.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Typically dimensions in a data warehouse are organized internally into one or more hierarchies.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A slowly changing dimension is a set of data attributes that change slowly over a period of time rather than changing regularly e.g. address or name.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] These attributes can change over a period of time and that will get combined as a slowly changing dimension.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A conformed dimension is a set of data attributes that have been physically referenced in multiple database tables using the same key value to refer to the same structure, attributes, domain values, definitions and concepts.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A conformed dimension cuts across many facts.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimensions are conformed when they are either exactly the same (including keys) or one is a proper subset of the other.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Conformed dimensions are either identical or strict mathematical subsets of the most granular, detailed dimension.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimension tables are not conformed if the attributes are labeled differently or contain different values.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Conformed dimensions come in several different flavors.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] At the most basic level, conformed dimensions mean exactly the same thing with every possible fact table to which they are joined.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension table connected to the sales facts is identical to the date dimension connected to the inventory facts.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A junk dimension is a convenient grouping of typically low-cardinality flags and indicators.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] By creating an abstract dimension, these flags and indicators are removed from the fact table while placing them into a useful dimensional framework.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A junk dimension is a dimension table consisting of attributes that do not belong in the fact table or in any of the existing dimension tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The nature of these attributes is usually text or various flags, e.g. non-generic comments or just simple yes/no or true/false indicators.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] These kinds of attributes are typically remaining when all the obvious dimensions in the business process have been identified and thus the designer is faced with the challenge of where to put these attributes that do not belong in the other dimensions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] One solution is to create a new dimension for each of the remaining attributes, but due to their nature, it could be necessary to create a vast number of new dimensions resulting in a fact table with a very large number of foreign keys.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The designer could also decide to leave the remaining attributes in the fact table but this could make the row length of the table unnecessarily large if, for example, the attribute is a long text string.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The solution to this challenge is to identify all the attributes and then put them into one or several junk dimensions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] One junk dimension can hold several true/false or yes/no indicators that have no correlation with each other, so it would be convenient to convert the indicators into a more describing attribute.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] An example would be an indicator about whether a package had arrived: instead of indicating this as “yes” or “no”, it would be converted into "arrived" or "pending" in the junk dimension.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The designer can choose to build the dimension table so it ends up holding all the indicators occurring with every other indicator so that all combinations are covered.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] This sets up a fixed size for the table itself which would be 2*x* rows, where *x* is the number of indicators.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] This solution is appropriate in situations where the designer would expect to encounter a lot of different combinations and where the possible combinations are limited to an acceptable level.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] In a situation where the number of indicators are large, thus creating a very big table or where the designer only expects to encounter a few of the possible combinations, it would be more appropriate to build each row in the junk dimension as new combinations are encountered.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] To limit the size of the tables, multiple junk dimensions might be appropriate in other situations depending on the correlation between various indicators.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Junk dimensions are also appropriate for placing attributes like non-generic comments from the fact table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Such attributes might consist of data from an optional comment field when a customer places an order and as a result will probably be blank in many cases.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Therefore, the junk dimension should contain a single row representing the blanks as a surrogate key that will be used in the fact table for every row returned with a blank comment field.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A degenerate dimension is a key, such as a transaction number, invoice number, ticket number, or bill-of-lading number, that has no attributes and hence does not join to an actual dimension table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Degenerate dimensions are very common when the grain of a fact table represents a single transaction item or line item because the degenerate dimension represents the unique identifier of the parent.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Degenerate dimensions often play an integral role in the fact table's primary key.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimensions are often recycled for multiple applications within the same database.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] For instance, a "Date" dimension can be used for "Date of Sale", as well as "Date of Delivery", or "Date of Hire".
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] This is often referred to as a "role-playing dimension".
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] This can be implemented using a view over the same dimension table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Usually dimension tables do not reference other dimensions via foreign keys.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] When this happens, the referenced dimension is called an outrigger dimension.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Outrigger dimensions should be considered a data warehouse anti-pattern: it is considered a better practice to use some fact tables that relate the two dimensions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A conformed dimensions is said to be a shrunken dimension when it includes a subset of the rows and/or columns of the original dimension.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A special type of dimension can be used to represent dates with a granularity of a day.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Dates would be referenced in a fact table as foreign keys to a date dimension.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension primary key could be a surrogate key or a number using the format YYYYMMDD.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension can include other attributes like the week of the year, or flags representing work days, holidays, etc.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] It could also include special rows representing: not known dates, or yet to be defined dates.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension should be initialized with all the required dates, say the next 10 years of dates, or more if required, or past dates if events in the past are handled.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Time instead is usually best represented as a timestamp in the fact table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] When referencing data from a metadata registry such as ISO/IEC 11179, representation terms such as "Indicator" (a Boolean true/false value), "Code" (a set of non-overlapping enumerated values) are typically used as dimensions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] For example, using the National Information Exchange Model (NIEM) the data element name would be "PersonGenderCode" and the enumerated values might be "male", "female" and "unknown".
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] In data warehousing, a dimension table is one of the set of companion tables to a fact table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The fact table contains business facts (or measures), and foreign keys which refer to candidate keys (normally primary keys) in the dimension tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Contrary to fact tables, dimension tables contain descriptive attributes (or fields) that are typically textual fields (or discrete numbers that behave like text).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] These attributes are designed to serve two critical purposes: query constraining and/or filtering, and query result set labeling.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimension table rows are uniquely identified by a single key field.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] It is recommended that the key field be a simple integer because a key value is meaningless, used only for joining fields between the fact and dimension tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimension tables often use primary keys that are also surrogate keys.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Surrogate keys are often auto-generated (e.g. a Sybase or SQL Server "identity column", a PostgreSQL or Informix serial, an Oracle SEQUENCE or a column defined with AUTO_INCREMENT in MySQL).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Although surrogate key use places a burden on the ETL system, pipeline processing can be improved, and ETL tools have built-in improved surrogate key processing.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The goal of a dimension table is to create standardized, conformed dimensions that can be shared across the enterprise's data warehouse environment, and enable joining to multiple fact tables representing various business processes.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Over time, the attributes of a given row in a dimension table may change.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] For example, the shipping address for a company may change.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Kimball refers to this phenomenon as slowly changing dimension.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Since many fact tables in a data warehouse are time series of observations, one or more date dimensions are often needed.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] One of the reasons to have date dimensions is to place calendar knowledge in the data warehouse instead of hard-coded in an application.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] While a simple SQL date-timestamp is useful for providing accurate information about the time a fact was recorded, it can not give information about holidays, fiscal periods, etc.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] An SQL date-timestamp can still be useful to store in the fact table, as it allows for precise calculations.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Having both the date and time of day in the same dimension, may easily result in a huge dimension with millions of rows.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] If a high amount of detail is needed it is usually a good idea to split date and time into two or more separate dimensions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A time dimension with a grain of seconds in a day will only have 86400 rows.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] A more or less detailed grain for date/time dimensions can be chosen depending on needs.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] As examples, date dimensions can be accurate to year, quarter, month or day and time dimensions can be accurate to hours, minutes or seconds.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] As a rule of thumb, time of day dimension should only be created if hierarchical groupings are needed or if there are meaningful textual descriptions for periods of time within the day (ex. “evening rush” or “first shift”).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] If the rows in a fact table are coming from several time zones, it might be useful to store date and time in both local time and a standard time.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] This can be done by having two dimensions for each date/time dimension needed – one for local time, and one for standard time.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] Storing date/time in both local and standard time, will allow for analysis on when facts are created in a local setting and in a global setting as well.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] The standard time chosen can be a global standard time (ex.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] UTC), it can be the local time of the business’ headquarters (ex.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimension-data-warehouse] CET), or any other time zone that would make sense to use.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Dimensional modeling always uses the concepts of facts (measures), and dimensions (context).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Facts are typically (but not always) numeric values that can be aggregated, and dimensions are groups of hierarchies and descriptors that define the facts.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] For example, sales amount is a fact; timestamp, product, register#, store#, etc. are elements of dimensions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Dimensional models are built by business process area, e.g. store sales, inventory, claims, etc.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Because the different business process areas share some but not all dimensions, efficiency in design, operation, and consistency, is achieved using conformed dimensions, i.e. using one copy of the shared dimension across subject areas.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Dimensional modeling does not necessarily involve a relational database.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] The same modeling approach, at the logical level, can be used for any physical form, such as multidimensional database or even flat files.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] It is oriented around understandability and performance.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] The dimensional model is built on a star-like schema or snowflake schema, with dimensions surrounding the fact table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] The process of dimensional modeling builds on a 4-step design method that helps to ensure the usability of the dimensional model and the use of the data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] The basics in the design build on the actual business process which the data warehouse should cover.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Therefore, the first step in the model is to describe the business process which the model builds on.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] This could for instance be a sales situation in a retail store.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] To describe the business process, one can choose to do this in plain text or use basic Business Process Model and Notation (BPMN) or other design guides like the Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] After describing the business process, the next step in the design is to declare the grain of the model.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] The grain of the model is the exact description of what the dimensional model should be focusing on.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] This could for instance be “An individual line item on a customer slip from a retail store”.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] To clarify what the grain means, you should pick the central process and describe it with one sentence.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Furthermore, the grain (sentence) is what you are going to build your dimensions and fact table from.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] You might find it necessary to go back to this step to alter the grain due to new information gained on what your model is supposed to be able to deliver.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] The third step in the design process is to define the dimensions of the model.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] The dimensions must be defined within the grain from the second step of the 4-step process.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Dimensions are the foundation of the fact table, and is where the data for the fact table is collected.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Typically dimensions are nouns like date, store, inventory etc.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] These dimensions are where all the data is stored.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] For example, the date dimension could contain data such as year, month and weekday.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] After defining the dimensions, the next step in the process is to make keys for the fact table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] This step is to identify the numeric facts that will populate each fact table row.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] This step is closely related to the business users of the system, since this is where they get access to data stored in the data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Therefore, most of the fact table rows are numerical, additive figures such as quantity or cost per unit, etc.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Dimensional normalization or snowflaking removes redundant attributes, which are known in the normal flatten de-normalized dimensions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Dimensions are strictly joined together in sub dimensions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] Snowflaking has an influence on the data structure that differs from many philosophies of data warehouses.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] 3NF databases suffer from performance problems when aggregating or retrieving many dimensional values that may require analysis.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] If you are only going to do operational reports then you may be able to get by with 3NF because your operational user will be looking for very fine grain data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] There are some arguments on why normalization can be useful.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] It can be an advantage when part of hierarchy is common to more than one dimension.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] For example, a geographic dimension may be reusable because both the customer and supplier dimensions use it.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] We still get the benefits of dimensional models on Hadoop and similar big data frameworks.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/dimensional-modeling] However, some features of Hadoop require us to slightly adapt the standard approach to dimensional modelling.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] In data warehousing, a **fact table** consists of the measurements, metrics or facts of a business process.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] It is located at the center of a star schema or a snowflake schema surrounded by dimension tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] Where multiple fact tables are used, these are arranged as a fact constellation schema.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] A fact table typically has two types of columns: those that contain facts and those that are a foreign key to dimension tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] The primary key of a fact table is usually a composite key that is made up of all of its foreign keys.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] Fact tables contain the content of the data warehouse and store different types of measures like additive, non-additive, and semi-additive measures.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] Fact tables (usually) provide the additive values that act as independent variables by which dimensional attributes are analyzed.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] Fact tables are often defined by their grain.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] The grain of a fact table represents the most atomic level by which the facts may be defined.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] The grain of a sales fact table might be stated as "sales volume by day by product by store".
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] Each record in this fact table is therefore uniquely defined by a day, product, and store.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] Other dimensions might be members of this fact table (such as location/region) but these add nothing to the uniqueness of the fact records.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] These "affiliate dimensions" allow for additional slices of the independent facts but generally provide insights at a higher level of aggregation (a region contains many stores).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] All foreign keys between fact and dimension tables should be surrogate keys, not reused keys from operational data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] A fact table might contain either detail-level facts or facts that have been aggregated (fact tables that contain aggregated facts are often instead called summary tables).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] Special care must be taken when handling ratios and percentages.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] One good design rule is to never store percentages or ratios in fact tables but only calculate these in the data access tool.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] Thus, only store the numerator and denominator in the fact table, which then can be aggregated, and the aggregated stored values can then be used for calculating the ratio or percentage in the data access tool.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] In the real world, it is possible to have a fact table that contains no measures or facts.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] These tables are called "factless fact tables", or "junction tables".
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] The *factless fact tables* may be used for modeling many-to-many relationships or for capturing timestamps of events.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] There are four fundamental measurement events, which characterize all fact tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] A transactional table is the most basic and fundamental.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] The grain associated with a transactional fact table is usually specified as "one row per line in a transaction", e.g., every line on a receipt.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] The periodic snapshot, as the name implies, takes a "picture of the moment", where the moment could be any defined period of time, e.g. a performance summary of a salesman over the previous month.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] A periodic snapshot table is dependent on the transactional table, as it needs the detailed data held in the transactional fact table in order to deliver the chosen performance output.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] This type of fact table is used to show the activity of a process that has a well-defined beginning and end, e.g., the processing of an order.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] An order moves through specific steps until it is fully processed.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] As steps towards fulfilling the order are completed, the associated row in the fact table is updated.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] An accumulating snapshot table often has multiple date columns, each representing a milestone in the process.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] Therefore, it's important to have an entry in the associated date dimension that represents a placeholder for an unknown date, as many of the milestone dates are unknown at the time of the creation of the row.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] allows to have the equivalent of daily snapshots without really having daily snapshots.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] It introduces the concept of time Intervals into a fact table, allowing saving a lot of space, optimizing performances while allowing the end user to have the logical equivalent of the "picture of the moment" they are interested in.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] **Declare the grain** – define exactly what a single fact-table row represents; different grains must not be mixed in one table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] **Identify the dimensions** that apply to each fact-table row.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] **Identify the facts (measures)** that are true to the declared grain.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] After the grain is declared, choose an appropriate fact-table type (e.g., transaction, periodic snapshot, accumulating snapshot).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/fact-table] This aggregate remains valid because the measure is additive and the fact rows share a single declared grain.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] In data management and data warehousing, a **slowly changing dimension** (SCD) is a dimension that stores data which, while generally stable, may change over time, often in an unpredictable manner.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] This contrasts with a **rapidly changing dimension**, such as transactional parameters like customer ID, product ID, quantity, and price, which undergo frequent updates.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Common examples of SCDs include geographical locations, customer details, or product attributes.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Various methodologies address the complexities of SCD management.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Ralph Kimball's Data Warehouse Toolkit has popularized a categorization of techniques for handling SCD attributes as Types 1 through 6.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] These range from simple overwrites (Type 1), to creating new rows for each change (Type 2), adding new attributes (Type 3), maintaining separate history tables (Type 4), or employing hybrid approaches (Type 6 and 7).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Type 0 is available to model an attribute as not really changing at all.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Each type offers a trade-off between historical accuracy, data complexity, and system performance, catering to different analytical and reporting needs.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The challenge with SCDs lies in preserving historical accuracy while maintaining data integrity and referential integrity.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] For instance, a fact table tracking sales might be linked to a dimension table containing information about salespeople and their assigned regional offices.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] If a salesperson is transferred to a new office, historical sales reports need to reflect their previous assignment without breaking the relationships between the fact and dimension tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] SCDs provide mechanisms to manage such changes effectively.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The Type 0 dimension attributes never change and are assigned to attributes that have durable values or are described as 'Original'.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Examples: *Date of Birth*, *Original Credit Score*.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Type 0 applies to most date dimension attributes.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] This method overwrites old with new data, and therefore does not track historical data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] In the above example, Supplier_Code is the natural key and Supplier_Key is a surrogate key.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Technically, the surrogate key is not necessary, since the row will be unique by the natural key (Supplier_Code).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The disadvantage of the Type 1 method is that there is no history in the data warehouse.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] It has the advantage however that it's easy to maintain.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] If one has calculated an aggregate table summarizing facts by supplier state, it will need to be recalculated when the Supplier_State is changed.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] This method tracks historical data by creating multiple records for a given natural key in the dimensional tables with separate surrogate keys and/or different version numbers.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Unlimited history is preserved for each insert.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The natural key in these examples is the "Supplier_Code" of "ABC".
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Another method is to add 'effective date' columns.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The Start date/time of the second row is equal to the End date/time (or next) of the previous row.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The null End_Date in row two indicates the current tuple version.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] A standardized surrogate high date (e.g.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] 9999-12-31) may instead be used as an end date so that null-value substitution is not required when querying.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] In some database software, using an artificial high date value could cause performance issues, that using a null value would prevent.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] And a third method uses an effective date and a current flag.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The Current_Flag value of 'Y' indicates the current tuple version.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Transactions that reference a particular surrogate key (Supplier_Key) are then permanently bound to the time slices defined by that row of the slowly changing dimension table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] An aggregate table summarizing facts by supplier state continues to reflect the historical state, i.e. the state the supplier was in at the time of the transaction; no update is needed.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] To reference the entity via the natural key, it is necessary to remove the unique constraint making referential integrity by DBMS (DataBase Management System) impossible.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] This can be an expensive database operation, so Type 2 SCDs are not a good choice if the dimensional model is subject to frequent change.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] This method tracks changes using separate columns and preserves limited history.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The Type 3 preserves limited history as it is limited to the number of columns designated for storing historical data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The original table structure in Type 1 and Type 2 is the same but Type 3 adds additional columns.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] In the following example, an additional column has been added to the table to record the supplier's original state - only the previous history is stored.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] This record contains a column for the original state and current state—cannot track the changes if the supplier relocates a second time.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] One variation of this is to create the field Previous_Supplier_State instead of Original_Supplier_State which would track only the most recent historical change.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The Type 4 method is usually referred to as using "history tables", where one table keeps the current data, and an additional table is used to keep a record of some or all changes.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Both the surrogate keys are referenced in the fact table to enhance query performance.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] This method resembles how database audit tables and change data capture techniques function.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The type 5 technique builds on the type 4 mini-dimension by embedding a “current profile” mini-dimension key in the base dimension that's overwritten as a type 1 attribute.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] This approach is called type 5 because 4 + 1 equals 5.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The type 5 slowly changing dimension allows the currently-assigned mini-dimension attribute values to be accessed along with the base dimension's others without linking through a fact table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Logically, we typically represent the base dimension and current mini-dimension profile outrigger as a single table in the presentation layer.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The outrigger attributes should have distinct column names, like “Current Income Level,” to differentiate them from attributes in the mini-dimension linked to the fact table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The ETL team must update/overwrite the type 1 mini-dimension reference whenever the current mini-dimension changes over time.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] If the outrigger approach does not deliver satisfactory query performance, then the mini-dimension attributes could be physically embedded (and updated) in the base dimension.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The Type 6 method combines the approaches of types 1, 2 and 3 (1 + 2 + 3 = 6).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] One possible explanation of the origin of the term was that it was coined by Ralph Kimball during a conversation with Stephen Pace from Kalido.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Ralph Kimball calls this method "Unpredictable Changes with Single-Version Overlay" in *The Data Warehouse Toolkit*.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The Current_State and the Historical_State are the same.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The optional Current_Flag attribute indicates that this is the current or most recent record for this supplier.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] We overwrite the Current_State information in the first record (Row_Key = 1) with the new information, as in Type 1 processing.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] We create a new record to track the changes, as in Type 2 processing.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] And we store the history in a second State column (Historical_State), which incorporates Type 3 processing.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] In many Type 2 and Type 6 SCD implementations, the surrogate key from the dimension is put into the fact table in place of the natural key when the fact data is loaded into the data repository.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The surrogate key is selected for a given fact record based on its effective date and the Start_Date and End_Date from the dimension table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] This allows the fact data to be easily joined to the correct dimension data for the corresponding effective date.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Once the Delivery table contains the correct Supplier_Key, it can easily be joined to the Supplier table using that key.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Having a Type 2 surrogate key for each time slice can cause problems if the dimension is subject to change.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] A pure Type 6 implementation does not use this, but uses a surrogate key for each master data item (e.g. each unique supplier has a single surrogate key).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] This avoids any changes in the master data having an impact on the existing transaction data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] It also allows more options when querying the transactions.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The following example shows how the query must be extended to ensure a single supplier record is retrieved for each transaction.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] A fact record with an effective date (Delivery_Date) of August 9, 2001 will be linked to Supplier_Code of ABC, with a Supplier_State of 'CA'.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] A fact record with an effective date of October 11, 2007 will also be linked to the same Supplier_Code ABC, but with a Supplier_State of 'IL'.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] If there is more than one date on the fact (e.g.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Order_Date, Delivery_Date, Invoice_Payment_Date) one can choose which date to use for a query.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] You can do "as at now", "as at transaction time" or "as at a point in time" queries by changing the date filter logic.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] You don't need to reprocess the fact table if there is a change in the dimension table (e.g. adding additional fields retrospectively which change the time slices, or if one makes a mistake in the dates on the dimension table one can correct them easily).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] You can introduce bi-temporal dates in the dimension table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] You can join the fact to the multiple versions of the dimension table to allow reporting of the same information with different effective dates, in the same query.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] The following example shows how a specific date such as '2012-01-01T00:00:00' (which could be the current datetime) can be used.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] An alternative implementation is to place *both* the surrogate key and the natural key into the fact table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] This method allows more flexible links to the dimension, even if one has used the Type 2 approach instead of Type 6.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] Different SCD Types can be applied to different columns of a table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/slowly-changing-dimension] For example, we can apply Type 1 to the Supplier_Name column and Type 2 to the Supplier_State column of the same table.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] In computing, the **star schema** or **star model** is the simplest style of data mart schema and is the approach most widely used to develop data warehouses and dimensional data marts.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] The star schema consists of one or more fact tables referencing any number of dimension tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] The star schema is an important special case of the snowflake schema, and is more effective for handling simpler queries.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] The star schema gets its name from the physical model's resemblance to a star shape with a fact table at its center and the dimension tables surrounding it representing the star's points.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] The star schema separates business process data into facts, which hold the measurable, quantitative data about a business, and dimensions which are descriptive attributes related to fact data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Examples of fact data include sales price, sale quantity, time, distance, speed and weight measurements.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Related dimension attribute examples include product models, product colors, product sizes, geographic locations, and salesperson names.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] A star schema that has many dimensions is sometimes called a *centipede schema*.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Having dimensions of only a few attributes, while simpler to maintain, results in queries with many table joins and makes the star schema less easy to use.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Fact tables record measurements or metrics for a specific event.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Fact tables generally consist of numeric values, and foreign keys to dimensional data where descriptive information is kept.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Fact tables are designed to a low level of uniform detail (referred to as "granularity" or "grain"), meaning facts can record events at a very atomic level.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] This can result in the accumulation of a large number of records in a fact table over time.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Fact tables are generally assigned a surrogate key to ensure each row can be uniquely identified.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Dimension tables usually have a relatively small number of records compared to fact tables, but each record may have a very large number of attributes to describe the fact data.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Dimension tables are generally assigned a surrogate primary key, usually a single-column integer data type, mapped to the combination of dimension attributes that form the natural key.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Star schemas are denormalized, meaning the typical rules of normalization applied to transactional relational databases are relaxed during star-schema design and implementation.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] A star schema denormalizes dimension attributes into single wide tables to improve understandability and reduce join complexity for analytic workloads.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] By contrast, a **snowflake schema** normalizes dimension hierarchies into multiple linked tables.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Kimball recommends avoiding snowflaking unless there is a clear need (for example, extremely large dimensions) because it adds complexity for users and can hurt query performance.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Star schemas align well with multidimensional/OLAP models commonly used in decision support.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Dimensional modeling distinguishes a central **fact table** and surrounding **dimension tables**.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Common fact table types in star schemas are **transaction**, **periodic snapshot**, and **accumulating snapshot**; frequently used conformed dimensions include date/time, product, customer, organization, and geography.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Analytic queries over a star schema usually join one large fact table with a handful of relatively small dimensions; many DBMSs implement ‘‘star-join’’ optimizations for this pattern.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Performance characteristics of such workloads are commonly studied using the **Star Schema Benchmark (SSB)**.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Consider a database of sales, perhaps from a store chain, classified by date, store and product.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] The image of the schema to the right is a star schema version of the sample schema provided in the snowflake schema article.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] `Fact_Sales` is the fact table and there are three dimension tables `Dim_Date`, `Dim_Store` and `Dim_Product`.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] Each dimension table has a primary key on its `Id` column, relating to one of the columns (viewed as rows in the example schema) of the `Fact_Sales` table's three-column (compound) primary key (`Date_Id`, `Store_Id`, `Product_Id`).
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] The non-primary key `Units_Sold` column of the fact table in this example represents a measure or metric that can be used in calculations and analysis.
[src:slowly-changing-dimension/star-schema] The non-primary key columns of the dimension tables represent additional attributes of the dimensions (such as the `Year` of the `Dim_Date` dimension).
